  "articleSummary": "**Summary:**  \nThe article explains that JavaScript promises behave fundamentally differently from ordinary values: you cannot log a promise directly and must use `.then` to access its resolved value. It warns that the TC39 design allowing `null` (or undefined) callbacks in `.then` and `.catch` makes it easy to introduce bugs, illustrated with a code quiz showing which forms correctly log `42`. The piece walks through the type differences between passing `console.log()` (which returns undefined) versus `console.log` (the function itself) and shows how a chain with an undefined handler simply passes the value onward. Intended for JavaScript developers—especially those new to async programming—the tone is tutorial‑style with a didactic, example‑driven approach, using the metaphor of “gotchas” to frame common pitfalls.",
